{"created": "2025-12-03T19:41:22.340556+00:00", "modified": "2025-12-03T19:41:23.125206+00:00", "id": 17806469, "conceptrecid": "17806468", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.17806469", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.17806468", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.17806469", "metadata": {"title": "TAILOR study", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.17806469", "publication_date": "2025-12-03", "description": "<p><strong>Background:&nbsp;</strong>Autoimmune hepatitis (AIH) is a rare, chronic inflammatory disease of the liver. The treatment goal is reaching complete biochemical response (CR), defined as the normalisation of aspartate and alanine aminotransferases and immunoglobulin gamma. Ongoing AIH activity can lead to fibrosis and (decompensated) cirrhosis. Incomplete biochemical response is the most important risk factor for liver transplantation or liver-related mortality. First-line treatment consists of a combination of azathioprine and prednisolone. If CR is not reached, tacrolimus (TAC) or mycophenolate mofetil (MMF) can be used as second-line therapy. Both products are registered for the prevention of graft rejection in solid organ transplant recipients. The aim of this study is to compare the effectiveness and safety of TAC and MMF as second-line treatment for AIH.</p>\n<p><strong>Methods:&nbsp;</strong>The TAILOR study is a phase IIIB, multicentre, open-label, parallel-group, randomised (1:1) controlled trial performed in large teaching and university hospitals in the Netherlands. We will enrol 86 patients with AIH who have not reached CR after at least 6 months of treatment with first-line therapy. Patients are randomised to TAC (0.07 mg/kg/day initially and adjusted by trough levels) or MMF (max 2000 mg/day), stratified by the presence of cirrhosis at inclusion. The primary endpoint is the difference in the proportion of patients reaching CR after 12 months. Secondary endpoints include the difference in the proportion of patients reaching CR after 6 months, adverse effects, difference in fibrogenesis, quality of life and cost-effectiveness.</p>\n<p><strong>Discussion:&nbsp;</strong>This is the first randomised controlled trial comparing two second-line therapies for AIH. Currently, second-line treatment is based on retrospective cohort studies. The rarity of AIH is the main issue in clinical research for alternative treatment options. The results of this trial can be implemented in existing international clinical guidelines.</p>", "access_right": "open", "creators": [{"name": "Tushuizen, Maarten", "affiliation": "Leiden University Medical Center", "orcid": "0000-0001-6342-9056"}, {"name": "van Hoek, Bart", "affiliation": "Leiden University", "orcid": "0000-0001-6527-764X"}], "contributors": [{"name": "van Hoek, Bart", "affiliation": "Leiden University", "type": "ProjectLeader", "orcid": "0000-0001-6527-764X"}, {"name": "Stoelinga, Anna", "affiliation": "Leiden University Medical Center", "type": "Researcher", "orcid": "0000-0002-3110-924X"}, {"name": "Tushuizen, Maarten", "affiliation": "Leiden University Medical Center", "type": "Supervisor", "orcid": "0000-0001-6342-9056"}], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "10.1186/s13063-023-07832-w", "relation": "isPublishedIn", "resource_type": "publication", "scheme": "doi"}], "dates": [{"type": "collected", "start": "2021 ", "end": " 2025"}], "language": "eng", "resource_type": {"title": "Dataset", "type": "dataset"}, "journal": {"issue": "1", "pages": "61", "title": "Trials", "volume": "25"}, "license": {"id": "cc-by-4.0"}, "grants": [{"code": "10140022010001", "internal_id": "01yaj9a77::10140022010001", "funder": {"name": "Netherlands Organisation for Health Research and Development"}, "title": "Rational Pharmacotherapy"}], "relations": {"version": [{"index": 0, "is_last": true, "parent": {"pid_type": "recid", "pid_value": "17806468"}}]}}, "title": "TAILOR study", "links": {"self": "https://zenodo.org/api/records/17806469", "self_html": "https://zenodo.org/records/17806469", "preview_htm